            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- INTELA-TRAUL BLOCK -->
  <section class="intela-section">
    <div class="container intela-inner">
      <div class="intela-text">
        <h2>INTELA-TRAUL — What It Is and What Fails</h2>
        <p>INTELA-TRAUL is Traulsen's proprietary microprocessor control system, found on G-series and RHT-series units. It's more sophisticated than the thermostatic controls on most competing commercial refrigerators — and more complex to diagnose when it fails.</p>
        <p><strong>What INTELA-TRAUL does:</strong> Continuous temperature monitoring with configurable alarm setpoints, door-ajar detection, defrost cycle management, temperature logging, and (on current units) remote monitoring via wired or wireless connection.</p>
        <p><strong>What typically fails:</strong> The control board itself accounts for roughly 35% of INTELA-TRAUL service calls. Temperature probe failure accounts for another 40% — the probe drifts or develops an open circuit, causing the board to display inaccurate temperatures or trigger false alarms. The remaining 25% are door switch failures, wiring connection issues, and user configuration errors.</p>
        <p><strong>Why power-cycling is not the answer:</strong> INTELA-TRAUL alarm states are designed to latch — they don't clear on power-cycle if the underlying fault is still present. Repeated power-cycling can stress the compressor start components. The right diagnostic sequence is fault code interpretation → probe check → board check → wiring check. We carry probe assemblies and compatible boards for the most common G-series vintages.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="intela-codes">
        <h3>Common INTELA-TRAUL Fault Indicators</h3>
        <div class="code-list">
          <div class="code-row">
            <span class="code-indicator">Flashing display</span>
            <span class="code-desc">Power interruption or board reset needed — check for recent outage</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-row">
            <span class="code-indicator">HI alarm</span>
            <span class="code-desc">Temperature above high setpoint — probe drift, door seal, or condenser</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-row">
            <span class="code-indicator">LO alarm</span>
            <span class="code-desc">Temperature below low setpoint — defrost cycle issue or probe calibration</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-row">
            <span class="code-indicator">DR alarm</span>
            <span class="code-desc">Door ajar — door switch or gasket not sealing</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-row">
            <span class="code-indicator">Blank display</span>
            <span class="code-desc">Board power failure or wiring issue — not a compressor problem</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-row">
            <span class="code-indicator">dEF display</span>
            <span class="code-desc">Active defrost cycle — normal operation, not a fault</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WARRANTY BLOCK -->
  <section class="warranty-section container">
    <h2>Traulsen Warranty — What It Covers and What Comes After</h2>
    <div class="warranty-grid">
      <div class="warranty-card active">
        <h3>Current Warranty Coverage</h3>
        <ul>
          {warrantyBlock.current.map(item => <li>{item}</li>)}
        </ul>
        <p class="warranty-note">Warranty service must be routed through Traulsen's authorized service network. We can advise on the correct process for warranty claims on units within the coverage period.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="warranty-card oowarranty">
        <h3>Out-of-Warranty Economics</h3>
        <p>{warrantyBlock.outOfWarranty}</p>
        <div class="cost-compare">
          <div class="cost-item">
            <span class="cost-label">New G24000R (2-door)</span>
            <span class="cost-val">$4,500–$6,000</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cost-item">
            <span class="cost-label">INTELA-TRAUL board</span>
            <span class="cost-val">$400–$700</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cost-item">
            <span class="cost-label">Door gasket set</span>
            <span class="cost-val">$150–$250</span>
          </div>
          <div class="cost-item">
            <span class="cost-label">Compressor replacement</span>
            <span class="cost-val">$800–$1,200</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- INDUSTRIES -->
  <section class="industries-section container">
    <h2>Who Runs Traulsen in SoCal</h2>
    <div class="industries-grid">
      <div class="industry-card">
        <h3>Fine Dining &amp; Chef-Driven Restaurants</h3>
        <p>LA's Michelin-starred and James Beard-recognized kitchens specify Traulsen for line-station reach-ins and blast chillers. When the reach-in behind the fish station fails during service, the kitchen stops. We prioritize fine dining service calls with the same urgency.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="industry-card">
        <h3>Hotels &amp; Resorts</h3>
        <p>Beverly Hills and Santa Monica resort kitchens — Shutters, the Biltmore, Beverly Wilshire — run Traulsen in banquet prep and main kitchen operations. Hotel facility managers working with multiple Traulsen units benefit from PM contracts covering all units on a coordinated schedule.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="industry-card">
        <h3>Healthcare &amp; Institutional</h3>
        <p>Cedars-Sinai, UCLA Health, Kaiser Permanente cafeteria operations, and affiliated hospital kitchens use Traulsen undercounters and reach-ins in food service areas. Healthcare maintenance schedules require documentation we provide with every service call.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="industry-card">
        <h3>University &amp; Culinary Programs</h3>
        <p>Culinary programs at Pasadena City College, CSCA, and the LA campus kitchens of major culinary schools run Traulsen as the teaching standard. Lab stations with 20-year-old Traulsen units that need INTELA-TRAUL board sourcing are a specialty call.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="industry-card">
        <h3>Catering Companies</h3>
        <p>LA's large-volume catering operations — production kitchens in Vernon, Commerce, and the Eastside industrial corridor — run Traulsen blast chillers as HACCP compliance equipment. Blast chiller failure stops production scheduling. We dispatch same-day on blast chiller calls.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="industry-card">
        <h3>Country Clubs &amp; Private Venues</h3>
        <p>LA and OC country clubs spec Traulsen in kitchen upgrades and maintain units for 15+ years. Long-service Traulsen equipment with discontinued INTELA-TRAUL board numbers requires cross-referencing compatible replacements — a specialty we've developed from repeated exposure.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
  <section class="repairs-section container">
    <h2>Recent Traulsen Service Calls</h2>
    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>"G24000R — HI alarm, not clearing, Beverly Hills restaurant"</h3>
        <p class="repair-loc">📍 Beverly Hills fine dining kitchen</p>
        <p>Two-door Traulsen reach-in showing persistent HI alarm despite unit holding 38°F on a secondary thermometer. INTELA-TRAUL temperature probe had drifted — reading 8 degrees warmer than actual cabinet temperature, triggering continuous alarm. Replaced the probe with an OEM Traulsen probe assembly, recalibrated the setpoints, cleared and tested the alarm system. Unit logging accurately. Restaurant's HACCP temperature records had been showing false high-temperature events for three weeks; the log was now clean.</p>
        <p class="repair-note"><em>INTELA-TRAUL probe drift: the probe reads warm, the alarm triggers, the compressor is fine. Always verify with independent thermometer.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>"TBC-10 blast chiller — not achieving pulldown, catering kitchen"</h3>
        <p class="repair-loc">📍 Vernon catering production facility</p>
        <p>Traulsen 10-pan blast chiller taking 3+ hours to pull cooked proteins to 40°F instead of the required 2 hours. Root cause: two of the three evaporator fan motors had failed, reducing airflow to 35% of rated capacity. Blast chillers depend on high-velocity air circulation — it's how they pull heat from food surface to center rapidly. Replaced both failed fan motors with OEM Traulsen parts, tested blast cycle timing — 105 minutes from 140°F to 38°F. HACCP compliance restored. The facility had been logging non-compliant pulldown times for 6 weeks without identifying the cause.</p>
        <p class="repair-note"><em>Blast chiller slow pulldown: always check fan motor count and speed before assuming refrigerant issue.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>"RHT232 half-door — upper section warmer than lower, hotel kitchen"</h3>
        <p class="repair-loc">📍 Santa Monica resort kitchen</p>
        <p>Traulsen half-door reach-in, upper section running 46°F, lower section 38°F — differential developed gradually over two months. Upper door gasket had developed compression failure at the top-left corner from the high-frequency opening pattern (upper section accessed more than lower in this kitchen's workflow). Cold air escaping from the upper section was causing the temperature differential. Replaced the upper section door gasket with an OEM Traulsen NSF-listed gasket. Upper section temperature equalized to 39°F within 2 hours.</p>
        <p class="repair-note"><em>Half-door units develop asymmetric gasket wear. The high-use section fails first — inspect both sections independently.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>"TUC-48-D-2 undercounter — blank INTELA-TRAUL display, hospital nursing station"</h3>
        <p class="repair-loc">📍 Cedars-Sinai affiliated facility</p>
        <p>15-year-old Traulsen undercounter at a nursing station, blank INTELA-TRAUL display. Unit was cooling (compressor running), but the control board had failed — display dark, no temperature readout, no alarm function. Original board was discontinued from the Traulsen parts network. Sourced a compatible INTELA-TRAUL replacement board from a verified secondary parts network, configured it for the unit's setpoints and alarm parameters, verified temperature logging function. Healthcare facility received documentation confirming restored monitoring compliance.</p>
        <p class="repair-note"><em>Discontinued INTELA-TRAUL boards: compatible replacements exist. Don't replace the unit — find someone who knows the architecture.</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="faq-section container">
    <h2>Traulsen Commercial Service — FAQ</h2>
